# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arikamedu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] An **amphora** (/ˈæmfərə/; Ancient Greek: ἀμφορεύς, romanized: **amphoreús**; English pl.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] **amphorae** or **amphoras**) is a type of storage and transport jar with a pointed bottom and characteristic shape and size which fit tightly (and therefore safely) against each other in storage rooms and packages, tied together with rope and delivered by land or sea.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Vessels of similar size and shape have been used from as early as the Neolithic Period.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphorae were used in vast numbers for the transport and storage of various products, both liquid and dry, but mostly for wine, olive oil, or garum.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Transport amphorae are ceramic, but examples of table amphorae in metal, glass, and other materials have been found.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Versions of the table amphorae were one of many shapes used in Ancient Greek vase painting.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Two types of amphorae existed: table amphorae, and transport or storage amphorae.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The amphora complements a large storage jar, the pithos (pl. pithoi), which makes available capacities between one-half and two and one-half tons.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In contrast, the amphora holds under a half-ton, typically less than 50 kilograms (110 lb).
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Where the pithos may have multiple small loops or lugs for fastening a rope harness, the amphora has two expansive handles joining the shoulder of the body and a long neck.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The necks of pithoi are wide for scooping or bucket access.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The necks of amphorae are narrow for pouring by a person holding it by the bottom and a handle.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The size may require two or three handlers to lift.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] For the most part, however, an amphora was tableware, or sat close to the table, was intended to be seen, and was finely decorated as such by master painters.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Stoppers made either of perishable materials, which have rarely survived, or of a refashioned potsherd, were used to seal the contents.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Two principal types of amphorae existed: the *neck amphora*, in which the neck and body meet at a sharp angle; and the *one-piece amphora*, in which the neck and body form a continuous curve upwards.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Neck amphorae were commonly used in the early history of ancient Greece, but were gradually replaced by the one-piece type from around the 7th century BC onward.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Most were produced with a pointed base to allow upright storage by embedding in soft ground, such as sand.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The base facilitated transport by ship, where the amphorae were packed upright or on their sides in as many as five staggered layers..
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] If upright, the bases probably were held by some sort of rack, and ropes passed through their handles to prevent shifting or toppling during rough seas.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Heather and reeds might be used as packing around the vases.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Racks could be used in kitchens and shops.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The base also concentrated deposits from liquids with suspended solid particles, such as olive oil and wines.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphorae are of great use to maritime archaeologists, as they often indicate the age of a shipwreck and the geographic origin of the cargo.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They are occasionally so well preserved that the original content is still present, providing information on foodstuffs and mercantile systems.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphorae were too cheap and plentiful to return to their origin-point and so, when empty, they were broken up at their destination.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] At a breakage site in Rome, Testaccio, close to the Tiber, the fragments, later wetted with calcium hydroxide (calce viva), remained to create a hill now named Monte Testaccio, 45 m (148 ft) high and more than 1 kilometre in circumference.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphora is a Greco-Roman word developed in ancient Greek during the Bronze Age.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The Romans acquired it during the Hellenization that occurred in the Roman Republic.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Cato the Younger is the first known literary person to use it.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The Romans turned the Greek form into a standard first declension noun, *amphora*, pl.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The word and the vase were almost certainly introduced to Italy through the Greek settlements there, which traded extensively in Greek pottery.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Even though the Etruscans imported, manufactured, and exported amphorae extensively in their wine industry, and other Greek vase names were Etruscanized, no Etruscan form of the word exists.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] There was perhaps an as yet unidentified native Etruscan word for the vase that pre-empted the adoption of *amphora*.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The Latin word derived from the Greek *amphoreus* (ἀμφορεύς), a shortened form of *amphiphoreus* (ἀμφιφορεύς), a compound word combining *amphi-* ("on both sides", "twain") and *phoreus* ("carrier"), from *pherein* ("to carry"), referring to the vessel's two carrying handles on opposite sides.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The amphora appears as 𐀀𐀠𐀡𐀩𐀸, *a-pi-po-re-we*, in the Linear B Bronze Age records of Knossos, 𐀀𐀡𐀩𐀸, *a-po-re-we*, at Mycenae, and the fragmentary *]-re-we* at Pylos, designated by Ideogram 209 𐃨, Bennett's AMPHORA, which has a number of scribal variants.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The two spellings are transcriptions of amphiphorēwes (plural) and amphorēwe (dual) in Mycenaean Greek from which it may be seen that the short form prevailed on the mainland.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Homer uses the long form for metrical reasons, and Herodotus has the short form.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The largest stands as tall as 1.5 metres (4.9 feet) high, while some were less than 30 centimetres (12 inches) high - the smallest were called amphoriskoi (literally "little amphorae").
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Most were around 45 centimetres (18 inches) high.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] There was a significant degree of standardisation in some variants; the wine amphora held a standard measure of about 39 litres (41 US qt), giving rise to the amphora quadrantal as a unit of measure in the Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In all, approximately 66 distinct types of amphora have been identified.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Further, the term also stands for an ancient Roman unit of measurement for liquids.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The volume of a Roman amphora (*amphora quadrantal*) was about one cubic *pes* (foot), equivalent to 26.2 liters (5.8 imp gal; 6.9 U.S. gal).
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Roman amphorae were wheel-thrown terracotta containers.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] During the production process the body was made first and then left to dry partially.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Then coils of clay were added to form the neck, the rim, and the handles.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Once the amphora was complete, the maker then treated the interior with resin that would prevent permeation of stored liquids.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The reconstruction of these stages of production is based primarily on the study of modern amphora production in some areas of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphorae often were marked with a variety of stamps, sgraffito, and inscriptions.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They provided information on the production, content, and subsequent marketing.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] A stamp usually was applied to the amphora at a partially dry stage.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] It indicates the name of the *figlina* (workshop) and/or the name of the owner of the workshop.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Painted stamps, *tituli picti*, recorded the weight of the container and the contents, and were applied after the amphora was filled.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Today, stamps are used to allow historians to track the flow of trade goods and recreate ancient trade networks.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The first systematic classification of Roman amphorae types was undertaken by the German scholar Heinrich Dressel.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Following the exceptional amphora deposit uncovered in Rome in Castro Pretorio at the end of the 1800s, he collected almost 200 inscriptions from amphorae and included them in the *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In his studies of the amphora deposit he was the first to elaborate a classification of types, the so-called "Dressel table", which still is used today for many types.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Subsequent studies on Roman amphorae have produced more detailed classifications, which usually are named after the scholar who studied them.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] For the neo-Phoenician types see the work by Maña published in 1951, and the revised classification by Van der Werff in 1977–1978.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The Gallic amphorae have been studied by Laubenheimer in a study published in 1989, whereas the Cretan amphorae have been analyzed by Marangou-Lerat.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Beltràn studied the Spanish types in 1970.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Adriatic types have been studied by Lamboglia in 1955.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] For a general analysis of the Western Mediterranean types see Panella, and Peacock and Williams.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Ceramics of shapes and uses falling within the range of amphorae, with or without handles, are of prehistoric heritage across Eurasia, from the Caucasus to China.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphorae dated to approximately 4800 BC have been found in Banpo, a Neolithic site of the Yangshao culture in China.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Amphorae first appeared on the Phoenician coast at approximately 3500 BC.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In the Bronze and Iron Ages amphorae spread around the ancient Mediterranean world, being used by the ancient Greeks and Romans as the principal means for transporting and storing grapes, olive oil, wine, oil, olives, grain, fish, and other agricultural products.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They were produced on an industrial scale until approximately the 7th century AD.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Wooden and skin containers seem to have supplanted amphorae thereafter.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They influenced Chinese ceramics and other East Asian ceramic cultures, especially as a fancy shape for high-quality decorative ceramics, and continued to be produced there long after they had ceased to be used further west.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Besides coarse amphorae used for storage and transport, the vast majority, high-quality painted amphorae were produced in Ancient Greece in significant numbers for a variety of social and ceremonial purposes.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Their design differs vastly from the more functional versions; they are typified by wide mouth and a ring base, with a glazed surface and decorated with figures or geometric shapes.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They normally have a firm base on which they can stand.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Panathenaic amphorae were used as prizes in the Panathenaic Festivals held between the 6th century BC to the 2nd century BC, filled with olive oil from a sacred grove.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Surviving examples bear the inscription "I am one of the prizes from Athens", and usually depict the particular event they were awarded for.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Painted amphorae were also used for funerary purposes, often in special types such as the *loutrophoros*.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Especially in earlier periods, outsize vases were used as grave markers, while some amphorae were used as containers for the ashes of the dead.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] By the Roman period vase-painting had largely died out, and utilitarian amphorae were normally the only type produced.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] On a neck amphora, the handles are attached to the neck, which is separated from the belly by an angular carination.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In contrast to the neck amphora, a belly amphora does not have a distinguished neck; instead, the belly reaches the mouth in a continuous curve.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] After the mid-5th century BC, this type was rarely produced.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The *pelike* is a special type of belly amphora, with the belly placed lower, so that the widest point of the vessel is near its bottom.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The *pelike* was introduced around the end of the 6th century BC.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Another special type is the Panathenaic prize amphora, with black-figure decoration, produced exclusively as prize vessels for the Panathenaia and retaining the black-figure technique for centuries after the introduction of red-figure vase painting.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Some examples bear the inscription "ΤΩΝ ΑΘΗΝΗΘΕΝ ΑΘΛΩΝ" meaning "[I am one] of the prizes from [the goddess] Athena".
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They contained the prize of oil from the sacred olive tree of the goddess Athena for the winners of the athletic contests held to honour the goddess, and were evidently kept thereafter, and perhaps used to store wine, before being buried with the prize-winner.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] They depicted goddess Athena on one side (as seen on the second image on this page) and the athletic event on the other side, e.g. a scene of wrestling or running contest etc.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] By the Roman period utilitarian amphorae were normally the only type produced.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The first type of Roman amphora, Dressel 1, appears in central Italy in the late 2nd century BC.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] This type had thick walls and a characteristic red fabric.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] It was very heavy, although also strong.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Around the middle of the 1st century BC the so-called Dressel 2-4 started to become used widely.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] This type of amphora presented some advantages in being lighter and with thinner walls.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] It has been calculated that while a ship could accommodate approximately 4500 Dressel 1, it was possible to fit 6000 Dressel 2–4 in the same space.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Dressel 2-4 were often produced in the same workshops used for the production of Dressel 1 which quickly ceased to be used.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] At the same time in Cuma (southern Italy) the production of the *cadii cumani* type starts (Dressel 21–22).
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] These containers were mainly used for the transportation of fruit and were used until the middle imperial period.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] At the same time, in central Italy, the so-called Spello amphorae, small containers, were produced for the transportation of wine.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] On the Adriatic coast the older types were replaced by the Lamboglia 2 type, a wine amphora commonly produced between the end of the 2nd and the 1st century BC.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] This type developed later into the Dressel 6A which becomes dominant during Augustan times.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In the Gallic provinces the first examples of Roman amphorae were local imitations of preexisting types such as Dressel 1, Dressel 2–4, Pascual 1, and Haltern 70.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The more typical Gallic production begins within the ceramic ateliers in Marseille during late Augustan times.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The type Oberaden 74 was produced to such an extent that it influenced the production of some Italic types.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Spanish amphorae became particularly popular thanks to a flourishing production phase in late Republican times.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The *Hispania Baetica* and *Hispania Tarraconensis* regions (south-western and eastern Spain) were the main production areas between the 2nd and the 1st century BC due to the distribution of land to military veterans and the founding of new colonies.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Spanish amphorae were widespread in the Mediterranean area during early imperial times.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The most common types were all produced in Baetica and among these there were the Dressel 20, a typical olive oil container, the Dressel 7–13, for garum (fish sauce), and the Haltern 70, for defrutum (fruit sauce).
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In the Tarraconensis region the Pascual 1 was the most common type, a wine amphora shaped on the Dressel 1, and imitations of Dressel 2–4.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] North-African production was based on an ancient tradition which may be traced back to the Phoenician colony of Carthage.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Phoenician amphorae had characteristic small handles attached directly onto the upper body.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] This feature becomes the distinctive mark of late-Republican/early imperial productions, which are then called neo-Phoenician.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The types produced in Tripolitania and Northern Tunisia are the Maña C1 and C2, later renamed Van der Werff 1, 2, and 3.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In the Aegean area the types from the island of Rhodes were quite popular starting from the 3rd century BC due to local wine production which flourished over a long period.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] These types developed into the *Camulodunum* 184, an amphora used for the transportation of Rhodian wine all over the empire.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Imitations of the Dressel 2-4 were produced on the island of Cos for the transportation of wine from the 4th century BC until middle imperial times.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Cretan containers also were popular for the transportation of wine and can be found around the Mediterranean from Augustan times until the 3rd century AD.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] During the late imperial period (3rd - 7th centuries AD), north-African types dominated amphora production in the west Mediterranean.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The so-called African I and II types were widely used from the 2nd until the late 4th century AD.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Production of Hispanic, Gallic, and Italic amphorae decreased greatly in the 5th and 6th centuries.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] In the east Mediterranean, several different varieties became extremely popular and nearly ubiquitous.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The Late Roman Amphora (LRA) 1 amphora was produced in Cilicia and Cypress, and traded all throughout the Mediterranean from the 5th to 6th centuries.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Other types from the eastern Mediterranean (Gaza), such as the so-called Late Roman 4, became very popular between the 4th and the 7th century AD, while Italic productions ceased.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] The largest known wreck of an amphorae cargo ship, carrying 6,000 pots, was discovered off the coast of Kefalonia, an Ionian island off the coast of Greece.
[src:arikamedu/amphorae] Some modern winemakers and brewers use amphorae to provide a different palate and taste to their products from those that are available with other aging methods.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-india] There are varying definitions of this period.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] During the 5th century, the Western Empire experienced a significant reduction of its territory.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Vandals conquered North Africa, the Visigoths claimed the southern part of Gaul, Gallaecia was taken by the Suebi, Britannia was abandoned by the central government, and the Empire suffered further from the invasions of Attila, chief of the Huns.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] General Orestes refused to meet the demands of the barbarian "allies" who now formed the army, and tried to expel them from Italy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Unhappy with this, their chieftain Odoacer defeated and killed Orestes, invaded Ravenna and dethroned Romulus Augustus, son of Orestes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] This event of 476, usually marks the end of Classical antiquity and beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman noble and former emperor Julius Nepos continued to rule as emperor from Dalmatia even after the deposition of Romulus Augustus until his death in 480.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Some historians consider him to be the last emperor of the Western Empire instead of Romulus Augustus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After 1200 years of independence and nearly 700 years as a great power, the rule of Rome in the West ended.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Various reasons for Rome's fall have been proposed, including loss of Republicanism, moral decay, military tyranny, class war, slavery, economic stagnation, environmental change, disease, the decline of the Roman race, as well as the inevitable ebb and flow that all civilisations experience.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Empire survived for almost 1000 years after the fall of its Western counterpart and became the most stable Christian realm during the Middle Ages.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] During the 6th century, Justinian reconquered the Italian peninsula from the Ostrogoths, North Africa from the Vandals, and southern Hispania from the Visigoths.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] But within a few years of Justinian's death, Byzantine possessions in Italy were greatly reduced by the Lombards who settled in the peninsula.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the east, partially due to the weakening effect of the Plague of Justinian as well as a series of mutually destructive wars against the Persian Sassanian Empire, the Byzantines were threatened by the rise of Islam.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Its followers rapidly brought about the conquest of the Levant, the conquest of North Africa and the conquest of Egypt during the Arab–Byzantine wars, and soon presented a direct threat to Constantinople.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the following century, the Arabs captured southern Italy and Sicily.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In the west, Slavic populations penetrated deep into the Balkans.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Byzantine Romans, however, managed to stop further Islamic expansion into their lands during the 8th century and, beginning in the 9th century, reclaimed parts of the conquered lands.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] In 1000 AD, the Eastern Empire was at its height: Basil II reconquered Bulgaria and Armenia, and culture and trade flourished.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] However, soon after, this expansion was abruptly stopped in 1071 with the Byzantine defeat in the Battle of Manzikert.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The aftermath of this battle sent the empire into a protracted period of decline.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] Two decades of internal strife and Turkic invasions ultimately led Emperor Alexios I Komnenos to send a call for help to the Western European kingdoms in 1095.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The West responded with the Crusades, eventually resulting in the Sack of Constantinople by participants of the Fourth Crusade.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of Constantinople in 1204 fragmented what remained of the Empire into successor states; the ultimate victor was the Empire of Nicaea.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] After the recapture of Constantinople by Imperial forces, the Empire was little more than a Greek state confined to the Aegean coast.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire collapsed when Mehmed the Conqueror conquered Constantinople on 29 May 1453.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The imperial city of Rome was the largest urban center in the empire, with a population variously estimated from 450,000 to close to one million.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Around 20% of the population under jurisdiction of ancient Rome (25–40%, depending on the standards used, in Roman Italy) lived in innumerable urban centers, with population of 10,000 and more and several military settlements, a very high rate of urbanisation by pre-industrial standards.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Most of those centers had a forum, temples, and other buildings similar to Rome's.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The average life expectancy in the Middle Empire was about 26–28 years.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The roots of the legal principles and practices of the ancient Romans may be traced to the Law of the Twelve Tables promulgated in 449 BC and to the codification of law issued by order of Emperor Justinian I around 530 AD (see *Corpus Juris Civilis*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law as preserved in Justinian's codes continued into the Byzantine Roman Empire, and formed the basis of similar codifications in continental Western Europe.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law continued, in a broader sense, to be applied throughout most of Europe until the end of the 17th century.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The major divisions of the law of ancient Rome, as contained within the Justinian and Theodosian law codes, consisted of *Jus civile*, *Jus gentium*, and *Jus naturale*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus civile* ('citizen law') was the body of common laws that applied to Roman citizens.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Urbanus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus gentium* ('law of nations') was the body of common laws that applied to foreigners, and their dealings with Roman citizens.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Peregrinus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens and foreigners.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] *Jus naturale* encompassed natural law, the body of laws that were considered common to all beings.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society is largely viewed as hierarchical, with slaves (*servi*) at the bottom, freedmen (*liberti*) above them, and free-born citizens (*cives*) at the top.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The broadest, and earliest, division was between the patricians, who could trace their ancestry to one of the 100 patriarchs at the founding of the city, and the plebeians, who could not.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] This became less important in the later Republic, as some plebeian families became wealthy and entered politics, and some patrician families fell economically.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Anyone, patrician or plebeian, who could count a consul as his ancestor was a noble (*nobilis*); a man who was the first of his family to hold the consulship, such as Marius or Cicero, was known as a *novus homo* ('new man') and ennobled his descendants.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Patrician ancestry, however, still conferred considerable prestige, and many religious offices remained restricted to patricians.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] A class division originally based on military service became more important.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Membership of these classes was determined periodically by the censors, according to property.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The wealthiest were the Senatorial class, who dominated politics and command of the army.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Next came the equestrians (*equites*, sometimes translated "knights"), originally those who could afford a warhorse, and who formed a powerful mercantile class.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Several further classes, originally based on the military equipment their members could afford, followed, with the *proletarii*, citizens who had no property other than their children, at the bottom.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Before the reforms of Marius they were ineligible for military service and are often described as being just above freed slaves in wealth and prestige.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Voting power in the Republic depended on class.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Citizens were enrolled in voting "tribes", but the tribes of the richer classes had fewer members than the poorer ones, all the *proletarii* being enrolled in a single tribe.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Voting was done in class order, from top down, and stopped as soon as most of the tribes had been reached, so the poorer classes were often unable to cast their votes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Women in ancient Rome shared some basic rights with their male counterparts, but were not fully regarded as citizens and were thus not allowed to vote or take part in politics.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] At the same time the limited rights of women were gradually expanded (due to emancipation) and women reached freedom from *pater familias*, gained property rights and even had more juridical rights than their husbands, but still no voting rights, and were absent from politics.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Allied foreign cities were often given the Latin Rights, an intermediary level between full citizens and foreigners (*peregrini*), which gave their citizens rights under Roman law and allowed their leading magistrates to become full Roman citizens.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] While there were varying degrees of Latin rights, the main division was between those *cum suffragio* ('with vote'; enrolled in a Roman tribe and able to take part in the *comitia tributa*) and *sine suffragio* ('without vote'; could not take part in Roman politics).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, there were no public schools, so boys were taught to read and write by their parents, or by educated slaves, called *paedagogi*, usually of Greek origin.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The primary aim of education during this period was to train young men in agriculture, warfare, Roman traditions, and public affairs.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Young boys learned much about civic life by accompanying their fathers to religious and political functions, including the Senate for the sons of nobles.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The sons of nobles were apprenticed to a prominent political figure at the age of 16, and campaigned with the army from the age of 17.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Educational practices were modified after the conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms in the 3rd century BC and the resulting Greek influence, although Roman educational practices were still much different from Greek ones.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning at age 12, students went to secondary schools, where the teacher (now called a *grammaticus*) taught them about Greek and Roman literature.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] At the age of 16, some students went on to rhetoric school (where the teacher, usually Greek, was called a *rhetor*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Education at this level prepared students for legal careers, and required that the students memorise the laws of Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Initially, Rome was ruled by kings, who were elected from each of Rome's major tribes in turn.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The exact nature of the king's power is uncertain.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] He may have held near-absolute power, or may have merely been the chief executive of the Senate and the people.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In military matters, the king's authority (*Imperium*) was likely absolute.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] He was also the head of the state religion.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The class struggles of the Roman Republic resulted in an unusual mixture of democracy and oligarchy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The word republic comes from the Latin *res publica*, which literally translates to 'public business'.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman laws traditionally could only be passed by a vote of the Popular assembly (Comitia Tributa).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Likewise, candidates for public positions had to run for election by the people.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, the Roman Senate represented an oligarchic institution, which acted as an advisory body.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the Republic, the Senate held actual authority (*auctoritas*), but no real legislative power; it was technically only an advisory council.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, as the Senators were individually very influential, it was difficult to accomplish anything against the collective will of the Senate.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] New senators were chosen from among the most accomplished patricians by censors (*Censura*), who could also remove a senator from his office if he was found "morally corrupt".
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Later, under the reforms of the dictator Sulla, quaestors were made automatic members of the Senate, though most of his reforms did not survive.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Republic had no fixed bureaucracy, and collected taxes through the practice of tax farming.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Government positions such as quaestor, aedile, or praefect were funded by the office-holder.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] To prevent any citizen from gaining too much power, new magistrates were elected annually and had to share power with a colleague.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] For example, under normal conditions, the highest authority was held by two consuls.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In an emergency, a temporary dictator could be appointed.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the Republic, the administrative system was revised several times to comply with new demands.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the end, it proved inefficient for controlling the ever-expanding dominion of Rome, contributing to the establishment of the Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Empire, the pretense of a republican form of government was maintained.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman emperor was portrayed as only a *princeps*, or 'first citizen', and the Senate gained legislative power and all legal authority previously held by the popular assemblies.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, the rule of the Emperors became increasingly autocratic, and the Senate was reduced to an advisory body appointed by the Emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire did not inherit a set bureaucracy from the Republic, since the Republic did not have any permanent governmental structures apart from the Senate.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor appointed assistants and advisers, but the state lacked many institutions, such as a centrally planned budget.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have cited this as a significant reason for the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] 500 BC) was, like those of other contemporary city-states influenced by Greek civilisation, a citizen *militia* that practised hoplite tactics.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] It was small and organised in five classes (in parallel to the *comitia centuriata*, the body of citizens organised politically), with three providing hoplites and two providing light infantry.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The early Roman army was tactically limited and its stance during this period was essentially defensive.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] By the 3rd century BC, the Romans abandoned the hoplite formation in favour of a more flexible system in which smaller groups of 120 (or sometimes 60) men called '*maniples* could manoeuvre more independently on the battlefield.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Thirty maniples arranged in three lines with supporting troops constituted a legion, totalling between 4,000 and 5,000 men.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The early Republican legion consisted of five sections: manipular heavy infantry (*hastati*, *principes* and *triarii*), a force of light infantry (*velites*), and the cavalry (*equites*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] With the new organisation came a new orientation toward the offensive and a much more aggressive posture toward adjoining city-states.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Until the late Republican period, the typical legionary was a property-owning citizen farmer from a rural area (an *adsiduus*) who served for particular (often annual) campaigns, and who supplied his own equipment.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] After 200 BC, economic conditions in rural areas deteriorated as manpower needs increased, so that the property qualifications for compulsory service were gradually reduced.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning in the 3rd century BC, legionaries were paid a stipend.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] By the time of Augustus, the ideal of the citizen-soldier had been abandoned and the legions had become fully professional.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] At the end of the Civil War, Augustus reorganised Roman military forces, discharging soldiers and disbanding legions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] He retained 28 legions, distributed through the provinces of the Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the Principate, the tactical organisation of the Army continued to evolve.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The *auxilia* remained independent cohorts, and legionary troops often operated as groups of cohorts rather than as full legions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] A new and versatile type of unit, the *cohortes equitatae*, combined cavalry and legionaries in a single formation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] They could be stationed at garrisons or outposts and could fight on their own as balanced small forces or combine with similar units as a larger, legion-sized force.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] This increase in organizational flexibility helped ensure the long-term success of Roman military forces.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor Gallienus (253–268 AD) began a reorganisation that created the last military structure of the late Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Withdrawing some legionaries from the fixed bases on the border, Gallienus created mobile forces (the *comitatenses*, or field armies) and stationed them behind and at some distance from the borders as a strategic reserve.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The border troops (*limitanei*) stationed at fixed bases continued to be the first line of defence.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of the field army were regimental; *legiones* or *auxilia* for infantry and *vexillationes* for cavalry.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Nominal strengths may have been 1,200 men for infantry regiments and 600 for cavalry, but actual troop levels could have been much lower—800 infantry and 400 cavalry.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Many infantry and cavalry regiments operated in pairs under the command of a *comes*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Field armies included regiments recruited from allied tribes and known as *foederati*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] By 400 AD, *foederati* regiments had become permanently established units of the Roman army, paid and equipped by the Empire, led by a Roman tribune and used just as Roman units were used.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire also used groups of barbarians to fight along with the legions as allies without integration into the field armies, under overall command of a Roman general, but led by their own officers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Military leadership evolved over the course of the history of Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Under the monarchy, the hoplite armies were led by the kings.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the early and middle Roman Republic, military forces were under the command of one of the two elected consuls for the year.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the later Republic, members of the Roman Senatorial elite, as part of the normal sequence of elected public offices known as the *cursus honorum*, would have served first as *quaestor* (often posted as deputies to field commanders), then as *praetor*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Following the end of a term as praetor or consul, a Senator might be appointed by the Senate as a *propraetor* or *proconsul* (depending on the highest office held before) to govern a foreign province.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Under Augustus, whose most important political priority was to place the military under a permanent and unitary command, the Emperor was the legal commander of each legion but exercised that command through a *legatus* (legate) he appointed from the Senatorial elite.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the later stages of the Imperial period (beginning perhaps with Diocletian), the Augustan model was abandoned.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Provincial governors were stripped of military authority, and command of the armies in a group of provinces was given to generals (*duces*) appointed by the Emperor.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] These were no longer members of the Roman elite but men who came up through the ranks and had seen much practical soldiering.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] With increasing frequency, these men attempted (sometimes successfully) to usurp the positions of the Emperors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Decreased resources, increasing political chaos and civil war eventually left the Western Empire vulnerable to attack and takeover by neighbouring barbarian peoples.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Less is known about the Roman navy than the Roman army.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Prior to the middle of the 3rd century BC, officials known as *duumviri navales* commanded a fleet of twenty ships used mainly to control piracy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] This fleet was given up in 278 AD and replaced by allied forces.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The First Punic War required that Rome build large fleets, and it did so largely with the assistance of and financing from allies.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] This reliance on allies continued to the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The quinquereme was the main warship on both sides of the Punic Wars and remained the mainstay of Roman naval forces until replaced by the time of Caesar Augustus by lighter and more manoeuvrable vessels.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Ships were commanded by a *navarch*, a rank equal to a centurion, who was usually not a citizen.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Potter suggests that because the fleet was dominated by non-Romans, the navy was considered non-Roman and allowed to atrophy in times of peace.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Information suggests that by the time of the late Empire (350 AD), the Roman navy comprised several fleets including warships and merchant vessels for transportation and supply.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Warships were oared sailing galleys with three to five banks of oarsmen.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Fleet bases included such ports as Ravenna, Arles, Aquilea, Misenum and the mouth of the Somme River in the West and Alexandria and Rhodes in the East.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Flotillas of small river craft (*classes*) were part of the *limitanei* (border troops) during this period, based at fortified river harbours along the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] That prominent generals commanded both armies and fleets suggests that naval forces were treated as auxiliaries to the army and not as an independent service.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The details of command structure and fleet strengths during this period are not well known, although fleets were commanded by prefects.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome commanded a vast area of land, with tremendous natural and human resources.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] As such, Rome's economy remained focused on farming and trade.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Agricultural free trade changed the Italian landscape, and by the 1st century BC, vast grape and olive estates had supplanted the yeoman farmers, who were unable to match the imported grain price.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The annexation of Egypt, Sicily and Tunisia in North Africa provided a continuous supply of grains.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In turn, olive oil and wine were Italy's main exports.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Two-tier crop rotation was practised, but farm productivity was low.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Industrial and manufacturing activities were small.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The largest such activities were the mining and quarrying of stones, which provided basic construction materials for the buildings of that period.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In manufacturing, production was on a relatively small scale, and generally consisted of workshops and small factories that employed at most dozens of workers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, some brick factories employed hundreds of workers.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The economy of the early Republic was largely based on smallholding and paid labour.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, foreign wars and conquests made slaves increasingly cheap and plentiful, and by the late Republic, the economy was largely dependent on slave labour for both skilled and unskilled work.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Slaves are estimated to have constituted around 20% of the Roman Empire's population at this time and 40% in the city of Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Only in the Roman Empire, when the conquests stopped and the prices of slaves increased, did hired labour become more economical than slave ownership.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Although barter was used in ancient Rome, and often used in tax collection, Rome had a very developed coinage system, with brass, bronze, and precious metal coins in circulation throughout the Empire and beyond—some have even been discovered in India.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Before the 3rd century BC, copper was traded by weight, measured in unmarked lumps, across central Italy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The original copper coins (*as*) had a face value of one Roman pound of copper, but weighed less.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, Roman money's utility as a unit of exchange consistently exceeded its intrinsic value as metal.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] After Nero began debasing the silver denarius, its legal value was an estimated one-third greater than its intrinsic value.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Horses were expensive and other pack animals were slower.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Mass trade on the Roman roads connected military posts, where Roman markets were centered.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] As a result, there was transport of commodities between Roman regions, but increased with the rise of Roman maritime trade in the 2nd century BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During that period, a trading vessel took less than a month to complete a trip from Gades to Alexandria via Ostia, spanning the entire length of the Mediterranean.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Transport by sea was around 60 times cheaper than by land, so the volume for such trips was much larger.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Some economists consider the Roman Empire a market economy, similar in its degree of capitalistic practices to the 17th-century Netherlands and 18th-century England.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of Roman society were households and families.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Groups of households connected through the male line formed a family (*gens*), based on blood ties, a common ancestry or adoption.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the Republic, some powerful families, or *Gentes Maiores*, came to dominate political life.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Families were headed by their oldest male citizen, the *pater familias* (father of the family), who held lawful authority (*patria potestas*, 'father's power') over wives, sons, daughters, and slaves of the household, and the family's wealth.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The extreme expressions of this power—the selling or killing of family members for moral or civil offences, including simple disobedience—were very rarely exercised, and were forbidden in the Imperial era.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] A *pater familias* had moral and legal duties towards all family members.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Even the most despotic *pater familias* was expected to consult senior members of his household and *gens* over matters that affected the family's well-being and reputation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, such matters were regarded as outside the purview of the state and its magistrates; under the emperors, they were increasingly subject to state interference and legislation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Once accepted into their birth family by their fathers, children were potential heirs.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] They could not be lawfully given away, or sold into slavery.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] If parents were unable to care for their child, or if its paternity was in doubt, they could resort to infant exposure (Boswell translates this as being "offered" up to care by the gods or strangers).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] If a deformed or sickly newborn was patently "unfit to live", killing it was a duty of the *pater familias*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] A citizen father who exposed a healthy freeborn child was not punished, but automatically lost his *potestas* over that child.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Abandoned children were sometimes adopted; some would have been sold into slavery.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Slavery was near-ubiquitous and almost universally accepted.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, citizens in debt were allowed to sell their labour, and perhaps their sons, to their debtor in a limited form of slavery called *nexum* but this was abolished in the middle Republic.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Freedom was considered a natural and proper state for citizens; slaves could be lawfully freed, with consent and support of their owners, and still serve their owners' family and financial interests, as freedmen or freed women.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] This was the basis of the client-patron relationship, one of the most important features of Rome's economy and society.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In law, a *pater familias* held *potestas* over his adult sons with their own households.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] This could give rise to legal anomalies, such as adult sons also having the status of minors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] No man could be considered a *pater familias*, nor could he truly hold property under law, while his own father lived.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During Rome's early history, married daughters came under the control (*manus*) of their husbands' *pater familias*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] By the late Republic, most married women retained lawful connection to their birth family, though any children from the marriage belonged to her husband's family.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The mother or an elderly relative often raised both boys and girls.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman moralists held that marriage and child-raising fulfilled a basic duty to family, *gens*, and the state.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Fathers usually began seeking husbands for their daughters when these reached an age between twelve and fourteen, but most commoner-class women stayed single until their twenties, and in general seem to have been far more independent than wives of the elite.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Divorce required the consent of one party, along with the return of any dowry.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Both parents had power over their children during their minority and adulthood, but husbands had much less control over their wives.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman citizen women held a restricted form of citizenship; they could not vote but were protected by law.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] They ran families, could own and run businesses, own and cultivate land, write their own wills, and plead in court on their own behalf, or on behalf of others, all under dispensation of the courts and the nominal supervision of a senior male relative.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The latter was much resented, and the former had seemingly negligible results.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Aristocratic women seem to have been increasingly disinclined to childbearing.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman hours were counted ordinally from dawn to dawn.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, if sunrise was at 6 am, then 6 to 7 am was called the 'first hour'.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Midday was called *meridies*, and it is from this word that the terms *am* (*ante meridiem*) and *pm* (*post meridiem*) stem.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The English word "noon" comes from *nona* ('ninth (hour)'), which referred to 3 pm in ancient Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had clocks (*horologia*), which included giant public sundials (*solaria*) and water clocks (*clepsydrae*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman week originally had eight days, which were identified by letters A to H, with the eighth day being the *nundinum*, or market day, a kind of weekend when farmers sold their produce on the streets.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The seven-day week, introduced from the East during the early Empire, was officially adopted during the reign of Constantine.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Romans named week days after celestial bodies from at least the 1st century AD.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman year originally had ten months from Martius (March) to December, with the winter period not included in the calendar.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The first four months were named after gods (Martius, Aprilis, Maius, Junius) and the others were numbered (Quintilis, Sextilis, September, October, November, and December).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Numa Pompilius, the second king of Rome (716–673 BC), is said to have introduced the months of January and February, both also named after gods, beginning the 12-month calendar still in use today.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In 44 BC, the month Quintilis was renamed to Julius (July) after Julius Caesar and in 8 BC, Sextilis was renamed to Augustus (August) after Augustus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had several ways of tracking years.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] One widespread way was the consular dating, which identified years by the two consuls who ruled each year.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, introduced in the late 3rd century AD, was counting years from the *indictio*, a 15-year period based on the announcement of the delivery of food and other goods to the government.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, less popular but more similar to present day, was *ab urbe condita*, which counted years from the mythical foundation of Rome in 753 BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Life in ancient Rome revolved around the city of Rome, located on seven hills.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The city had a vast number of monumental structures like the Colosseum, the Trajan's Forum and the Pantheon.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] It had theatres, gymnasiums, marketplaces, functional sewers, bath complexes complete with libraries and shops, and fountains with fresh drinking water supplied by hundreds of miles of aqueducts.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the territory under the control of ancient Rome, residential architecture ranged from modest houses to country villas.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, there were imperial residences on Palatine Hill.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The low plebeian and middle equestrian classes lived in the city center, packed into apartments, or insulae, which were almost like modern ghettos.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] These areas, often built by upper class property owners to rent, were often centred upon collegia or taberna.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] These people, provided with a free supply of grain, and entertained by gladiatorial games, were enrolled as clients of patrons among the upper class patricians, whose assistance they sought and whose interests they upheld.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The native language of the Romans was Latin, an Italic language the grammar of which relies little on word order, conveying meaning through a system of affixes attached to word stems.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Its alphabet was based on the Etruscan alphabet, which was in turn based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Speakers of Latin could understand both until the 7th century when spoken Latin began to diverge so much that 'Classical' or 'Good Latin' had to be learned as a second language.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] While Latin remained the main written language of the Roman Empire, Greek came to be the language spoken by the well-educated elite, as most of the literature studied by Romans was written in Greek.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Most of the emperors were bilingual but had a preference for Latin in the public sphere for political reasons, a practice that first started during the Punic wars.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the eastern part of the Roman Empire (and later the Eastern Roman Empire), Latin was never able to replace Greek, a legacy of the Hellenistic period.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Justinian would be the last emperor to use Latin in government and marks when Greek officially took over.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The expansion of the Roman Empire spread Latin throughout Europe, and Vulgar Latin evolved into many distinct Romance languages.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Archaic Roman religion, at least concerning the gods, was made up not of written narratives, but rather of complex interrelations between gods and humans.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Unlike in Greek mythology, the gods were not personified, but were vaguely defined sacred spirits called *numina*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Romans also believed that every person, place or thing had its own *genius*, or divine soul.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the Roman Republic, Roman religion was organised under a strict system of priestly offices, which were held by men of senatorial rank.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The College of Pontifices was uppermost body in this hierarchy, and its chief priest, the *Pontifex Maximus*, was the head of the state religion.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Flamens took care of the cults of various gods, while augurs were trusted with taking the auspices.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The sacred king took on the religious responsibilities of the deposed kings.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman Empire, deceased emperors who had ruled well were deified by their successors and the Senate. and the formalised imperial cult became increasingly prominent.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] As contact with the Greeks increased, the old Roman gods became increasingly associated with Greek gods.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Under the Empire, the Romans absorbed the mythologies of their conquered subjects, often leading to situations in which the temples and priests of traditional Italian deities existed side by side with those of foreign gods.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning with Emperor Nero in the 1st century AD, Roman official policy towards Christianity was negative, and at some point, being a Christian could be punishable by death.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Under Emperor Diocletian, the persecution of Christians reached its peak.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, it became an officially supported religion in the Roman state under Diocletian's successor, Constantine I, with the signing of the Edict of Milan in 313, and quickly became dominant.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] All religions except Christianity were prohibited in 391 AD by an edict of Emperor Theodosius I.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Like many ancient cultures, concepts of ethics and morality, while sharing some commonalities with modern society, differed greatly in several important ways.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Because ancient civilisations like Rome were under constant threat of attack from marauding tribes, their culture was necessarily militaristic with martial skills being a prized attribute.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Whereas modern societies consider compassion a virtue, Roman society considered compassion a vice, a moral defect.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] One of the primary purposes of the gladiatorial games was to inoculate Roman citizens from this weakness.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Romans instead prized virtues such as courage and conviction (*virtus*), a sense of duty to one's people, moderation and avoiding excess (*moderatio*), forgiveness and understanding (*clementia*), fairness (*severitas*), and loyalty (*pietas*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society had well-established and restrictive norms related to sexuality, though as with many societies, the lion's share of the responsibilities fell on women.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Women were generally expected to be monogamous having only a single husband during their life (*univira*), though this was much less regarded by the elite, especially under the empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Women were expected to be modest in public avoiding any provocative appearance and to demonstrate absolute fidelity to their husbands (*pudicitia*).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Wearing a veil was a common expectation to preserve modesty.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Sex outside of marriage was generally frowned upon for men and women and was made illegal during the imperial period.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Nevertheless, prostitution was an accepted and regulated practice.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Public demonstrations of death, violence, and brutality were used as a source of entertainment in Roman communities; however it was also a way to maintain social order, demonstrate power, and signify communal unity.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman painting styles show Greek influences, and surviving examples are primarily frescoes used to adorn the walls and ceilings of country villas, though Roman literature includes mentions of paintings on wood, ivory, and other materials.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Several examples of Roman painting have been found at Pompeii, and from these art historians divide the history of Roman painting into four periods.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The first style of Roman painting was practised from the early 2nd century BC to the early- or mid-1st century BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] It was mainly composed of imitations of marble and masonry, though sometimes including depictions of mythological characters.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The second style began during the early 1st century BC and attempted to depict realistically three-dimensional architectural features and landscapes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The third style occurred during the reign of Augustus (27 BC – 14 AD), and rejected the realism of the second style in favour of simple ornamentation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] A small architectural scene, landscape, or abstract design was placed in the center with a monochrome background.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The fourth style, which began in the 1st century AD, depicted scenes from mythology, while retaining architectural details and abstract patterns.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Portrait sculpture used youthful and classical proportions, evolving later into a mixture of realism and idealism.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the Antonine and Severan periods, ornate hair and bearding, with deep cutting and drilling, became popular.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were also made in relief sculptures, usually depicting Roman victories.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman music was largely based on Greek music, and played an important part in many aspects of Roman life.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman military, musical instruments such as the *tuba* (a long trumpet) or the *cornu* were used to give various commands, while the *buccina* (possibly a trumpet or horn) and the *lituus* (probably an elongated J-shaped instrument), were used in ceremonial capacities.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Music was used in the Roman amphitheatres between fights and in the *odea*, and in these settings is known to have featured the *cornu* and the *hydraulis* (a type of water organ).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Most religious rituals featured musical performances.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Some music historians believe that music was used at almost all public ceremonies.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The graffiti, brothels, paintings, and sculptures found in Pompeii and Herculaneum suggest that the Romans had a sex-saturated culture.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Latin literature was, from its start, influenced heavily by Greek authors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Some of the earliest extant works are of historical epics telling the early military history of Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] As the Republic expanded, authors began to produce poetry, comedy, history, and tragedy.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome's literary contributions are still recognised today and the works by ancient Roman authors were available in bookshops as well as in public and private libraries.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Many scholars and statesmen of ancient Rome cultivated private libraries that were used both as demonstrations of knowledge and displays of wealth and power.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Although Julius Caesar had intended to establish public libraries to further establish Rome as a great cultural center like Athens and Alexandria, he died before this was accomplished.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Caesar's former lieutenant, Gaius Asinius Pollio, took up the project and opened the first public library in Rome in the Atrium Libertatis.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Emperors Augustus, Tiberius, Vespasian, Domitian, and Trajan also founded or expanded public libraries in Rome during their reigns.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] These included the Ulpian Library in Trajan's Forum and libraries in the Temple of Apollo Palatinus, the Temple of Peace in the Roman Forum, the Temple of Divus Augustus, which was dedicated to Minerva when it was rebuilt under Emperor Domitian's orders.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] By the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the city of Rome had more than two dozen public libraries.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] As the Roman Empire spread, public libraries were established in other major cities and cultural centers including Ephesos, Athens, and Timgad.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Roman cuisine changed over the long duration of this ancient civilisation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Dietary habits were affected by the influence of Greek culture, the political changes from Kingdom to Republic to Empire, and the Empire's enormous expansion, which exposed Romans to many new, provincial culinary habits and cooking techniques.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the beginning the differences between social classes were relatively small, but disparities evolved with the Empire's growth.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Men and women drank wine with their meals.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman diet included many items that are staples of modern Italian cooking.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] However, some foods now considered characteristic of modern Italian cuisine were not used.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In particular, spinach and eggplant (aubergine) were introduced later from the Arab world, and tomatoes, potatoes, capsicum peppers, and maize (the modern source of polenta) only appeared in Europe following the discovery of the New World and the Columbian Exchange.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans knew of rice, but it was very rarely available to them.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Butcher's meat such as beef was an uncommon luxury.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The most popular meat was pork, especially sausages.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Fish was more common than meat, with a sophisticated aquaculture and large-scale industries devoted to oyster farming.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also engaged in snail farming and oak grub farming.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Some fish were greatly esteemed and fetched high prices, such as mullet raised in the fishery at Cosa, and "elaborate means were invented to assure its freshness".
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, a breakfast called *ientaculum* was served at dawn.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] At mid-day to early afternoon, Romans ate *cena*, the main meal of the day, and at nightfall a light supper called *vesperna*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] With the increased importation of foreign foods, the *cena* grew larger in size and included a wider range of foods.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, it gradually shifted to the evening, while the *vesperna* was abandoned completely over the course of the years.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The mid-day meal *prandium* became a light meal to hold one over until *cena*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The toga, a common garment during the era of Julius Caesar, was gradually abandoned by all social classes of the Empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] At the early 4th century, the toga had become just a garment worn by senators in Senate and ceremonial events.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] At the 4th century, the toga was replaced by the *paenula* (a garment similar to a poncho) as the everyday garment of the Romans, from the lower classes to the upper classes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Another garment that was popular among the Romans in the later years of the Western Roman Empire was the *pallium*, which was mostly worn by philosophers and scholars in general.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Due to external influences, mainly from the Germanic peoples, the Romans adopted tunics very similar to those used by the Germanic peoples with whom they interacted in the final years of the Western Empire, also adopted trousers and hats like the *pileus pannonicus*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] During the Late Empire, the *paludamentum* (a type of military clothing) was used only by the Emperor of Rome (since the reign of Augustus, the first emperor) while the dalmatic (also used by the Christian clergy) began to spread throughout the empire.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The youth of Rome had several forms of athletic play and exercise.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Play for boys was supposed to prepare them for active military service, such as jumping, wrestling, boxing, and racing.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the countryside, pastimes for the wealthy also included fishing and hunting.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also had several forms of ball playing, including one resembling handball.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Dice games, board games, and gamble games were popular pastimes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] For the wealthy, dinner parties presented an opportunity for entertainment, sometimes featuring music, dancing, and poetry readings.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The majority, less well-off, sometimes enjoyed similar parties through clubs or associations, but for most Romans, recreational dining usually meant patronising taverns.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Children entertained themselves with toys and such games as leapfrog.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Public games and spectacles were sponsored by leading Romans who wished to advertise their generosity and court popular approval; in Rome or its provinces, this usually meant the emperor or his governors.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Venues in Rome and the provinces were developed specifically for public games.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Rome's Colosseum was built in 70 AD under the Roman emperor Vespasian and opened in 80 AD to host other events and gladiatorial combats.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Gladiators sometimes fought to the death, but more often to an adjudicated victory, usually in keeping with the mood of the watching crowd.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Shows of exotic animals were popular in their own right; but sometimes animals were pitted against human beings, either armed professionals or unarmed criminals who had been condemned to public death.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Chariot racing was extremely popular among all classes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, these races were usually held at the Circus Maximus, which had been purpose-built for chariot and horse-racing and, as Rome's largest public place, was also used for festivals and animal shows.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome boasted impressive technological feats, using many advancements that were lost in the Middle Ages and not rivalled again until the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] An example of this is insulated glazing, which was not invented again until the 1930s.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Many practical Roman innovations were adopted from earlier Greek designs.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were often divided and based on craft.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Artisans guarded technologies as trade secrets.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Roman civil engineering and military engineering constituted a large part of Rome's technological superiority and legacy, and contributed to the construction of hundreds of roads, bridges, aqueducts, public baths, theatres and arenas.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Many monuments, such as the Colosseum, Pont du Gard, and Pantheon, remain as testaments to Roman engineering and culture.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans were renowned for their architecture, which is grouped with Greek traditions into "Classical architecture".
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Although there were many differences from Greek architecture, Rome borrowed heavily from Greece in adhering to strict, formulaic building designs and proportions.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Aside from two new orders of columns, composite and Tuscan, and from the dome, which was derived from the Etruscan arch, Rome had relatively few architectural innovations until the end of the Republic.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] In the 1st century BC, Romans started to use Roman concrete widely.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Concrete was invented in the late 3rd century BC.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] It was a powerful cement derived from pozzolana, and soon supplanted marble as the chief Roman building material and allowed many daring architectural forms.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Also in the 1st century BC, Vitruvius wrote *De architectura*, possibly the first complete treatise on architecture in history.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also largely built using timber, causing a rapid decline of the woodlands surrounding Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] It is suggested that timber, around 4 metres (13 ft) long, came up to Rome via the Tiber River on ships travelling across the Mediterranean Sea from the confluence of the Saône and Rhône rivers in what is now the city of Lyon in present-day France.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] With solid foundations and good drainage, Roman roads were known for their durability and many segments of the Roman road system were still in use a thousand years after the fall of Rome.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The construction of a vast and efficient travel network throughout the Empire dramatically increased Rome's power and influence.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] They allowed Roman legions to be deployed rapidly, with predictable marching times between key points of the empire, no matter the season.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] These highways also had enormous economic significance, solidifying Rome's role as a trading crossroads—the origin of the saying "all roads lead to Rome".
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman government maintained a system of way stations, known as the *cursus publicus*, and established a system of horse relays allowing a dispatch to travel up to 80 km (50 mi) a day.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans constructed numerous aqueducts to supply water to cities and industrial sites and to aid in their agriculture.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] By the third century, the city of Rome was supplied by 11 aqueducts with a combined length of 450 km (280 mi).
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also made major advancements in sanitation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Romans were particularly famous for their public baths, called *thermae*, which were used for both hygienic and social purposes.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Many Roman houses had flush toilets and indoor plumbing, and a complex sewer system, the *Cloaca Maxima*, was used to drain the local marshes and carry waste into the Tiber.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have speculated that lead pipes in the sewer and plumbing systems led to widespread lead poisoning, which contributed to fall of Rome; however, lead content would have been minimised.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Ancient Rome is the progenitor of Western civilisation.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] The customs, religion, law, technology, architecture, political system, military, literature, languages, alphabet, government and many factors and aspects of western civilisation are all inherited from Roman advancements.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] The rediscovery of Roman culture revitalised Western civilisation, playing a role in the Renaissance and the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] The two longest ancient accounts of the Roman history, the histories of Livy and Dionysius of Halicarnassus, were composed 500 years later than the date for the founding of the republic and 200 years from the defeat of Hannibal.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Although there has been a diversity of works on ancient Roman history, many of them are lost.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] As a result of this loss, there are gaps in Roman history, which are filled by unreliable works, such as the **Historia Augusta**.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Caesar wrote his own accounts of his military campaigns in Gaul and during the Civil War in part to impress his contemporaries.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] In the Empire, the biographies of famous men and early emperors flourished, examples being *The Twelve Caesars* of Suetonius, and Plutarch's *Parallel Lives*.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Other major works of Imperial times were that of Livy and Tacitus.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Interest in studying, and idealising, ancient Rome became prevalent during the Italian Renaissance.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Edward Gibbon's *The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* "began the modern study of Roman history in the English-speaking world".
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] Barthold Georg Niebuhr was a founder of the examination of ancient Roman history and wrote *The Roman History*, tracing the period until the First Punic War.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] During the Napoleonic, *The History of Romans* by Victor Duruy highlighted the Caesarean period popular at the time.
[src:arikamedu/ancient-rome-p03] *History of Rome*, *Roman constitutional law* and *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*, all by Theodor Mommsen, became milestones.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] An **archaeological site** is a place (or group of physical sites) in which evidence of past activity is preserved (either prehistoric or historic or contemporary), and which has been, or may be, investigated using the discipline of archaeology and represents a part of the archaeological record.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Sites may range from those with few or no remains visible above ground, to buildings and other structures still in use.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Beyond this, the definition and geographical extent of a "site" can vary widely, depending on the period studied and the theoretical approach of the archaeologist.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It is almost invariably difficult to delimit a site.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It is sometimes taken to indicate a settlement of some sort, although the archaeologist must also define the limits of human activity around the settlement.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Any episode of deposition, such as a hoard or burial, can form a site as well.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Development-led archaeology undertaken as cultural resources management has the disadvantage (or the benefit) of having its sites defined by the limits of the intended development.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Even in this case, however, in describing and interpreting the site, the archaeologist will have to look outside the boundaries of the building site.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] According to Jess Beck in "How Do Archaeologists Find Sites?", areas with numerous artifacts are good targets for future excavation, while areas with a small number of artifacts are thought to reflect a lack of past human activity.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Many areas have been discovered by accident.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] The most common people who have found artifacts are farmers who are plowing their fields or just cleaning them up, and they often find archaeological artifacts.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Many people who are out hiking and even pilots find artifacts, and they usually end up reporting them to archaeologists for further investigation.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] When they find sites, they have to first record the area, and if they have the money and time for the site, they can begin digging.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] There are many ways to find sites, one example can be through surveys.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Surveys involve walking around analyzing the land and looking for artifacts.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It can also involve digging, according to the Archaeological Institute of America, "archaeologists actively search areas that were likely to support human populations, or in places where old documents and records indicate people once lived." This helps archaeologists in the future.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] In case there is no time or money during the site's discovery, archaeologists can come back and visit the site for further digging to find out the extent of the site.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Archaeologist can also sample randomly within a given area of land as another form of conducting surveys.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Surveys are very useful, according to Jess Beck, "it can tell you where people were living at different points in the past.Geophysics is a branch of survey becoming more and more popular in archaeology, because it uses different types of instruments to investigate features below the ground surface.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It is not as reliable because although they can see what is under the surface of the ground, it does not produce the best picture.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Archaeologists still have to dig up the area in order to uncover the truth.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] There are also two most common types of geophysical survey, which is, magnetometer and ground penetrating radar.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Magnetometry is the technique of measuring and mapping patterns of magnetism in the soil.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It uses an instrument called a magnetometer, which is required to measure and map traces of soil magnetism.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] The ground penetrating radar is a method that uses radar pulses to image the subsurface.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It uses electromagnetic radiation in the microwave band of the radio spectrum and detects the reflected signals from subsurface structures.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] There are many other tools that can be used to find artifacts, but along with finding artifacts, archaeologists have to make maps.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] They do so by taking data from surveys, or archival research and plugging it into a Geographical Information Systems (GIS) and that will contain both locational information and a combination of various information.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] This tool is very helpful to archaeologists who want to explore in a different area and want to see if anyone else has done research.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] They can use this tool to see what has already been discovered.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] With this information available, archaeologists can expand their research and add more to what has already been found.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Traditionally, sites are distinguished by the presence of both artifacts and features.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Common features include the remains of hearths and houses.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Ecofacts, biological materials (such as bones, scales, and even feces) that are the result of human activity but are not deliberately modified, are also common at many archaeological sites.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] In the cases of the Palaeolithic and Mesolithic eras, a mere scatter of flint flakes will also constitute a site worthy of study.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Different archaeologists may see an ancient town, and its nearby cemetery as being two different sites, or as being part of the same wider site.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] The precepts of landscape archaeology attempt to see each discrete unit of human activity in the context of the wider environment, further distorting the concept of the site as a demarcated area.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Furthermore, geoarchaeologists or environmental archaeologists would also consider a sequence of natural geological or organic deposition, in the absence of human activity, to constitute a site worthy of study.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Archaeological sites usually form through human-related processes but can be subject to natural, post-depositional factors.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Cultural remnants which have been buried by sediments are, in many environments, more likely to be preserved than exposed cultural remnants.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Natural actions resulting in sediment being deposited include alluvial (water-related) or aeolian (wind-related) natural processes.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] In jungles and other areas of lush plant growth, decomposed vegetative sediment can result in layers of soil deposited over remains.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Colluviation, the burial of a site by sediments moved by gravity (called hillwash) can also happen at sites on slopes.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Human activities (both deliberate and incidental) also often bury sites.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] It is common in many cultures for newer structures to be built atop the remains of older ones.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Urban archaeology has developed especially to deal with these sorts of site.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Many sites are the subject of ongoing excavation or investigation.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-site] Note the difference between archaeological sites and archaeological discoveries.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The **Archaeological Survey of India** (**ASI**) is an Indian government agency that is responsible for archaeological research and the conservation and preservation of cultural historical monuments in the country.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] It was founded in 1861 by Alexander Cunningham during the British Raj who also became its first Director-General.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] ASI was founded in 1861 by Alexander Cunningham who also became its first Director-General.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The first systematic research into the subcontinent's history was conducted by the Asiatic Society, which was founded by the British Indologist Sir William Jones on 15 January 1784.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Based in Calcutta, the society promoted the study of ancient Persian texts and published an annual journal titled *Asiatic Researches*.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Notable among its early members was Charles Wilkins who published the first English translation of the *Bhagavad Gita* in 1785 with the patronage of the then Governor-General of Bengal, Warren Hastings.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Jones initiative resulted in the publication of *Asiatick Researches*, a monthly that was launched in 1788.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Marquis of Wellesley's 1800 nomination of Francis Buchanan to survey Mysore was a wise move on the part of the administration at the time.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] He was hired in 1807 to investigate historical sites and monuments in what is now Uttar Pradesh and Bihar.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The first attempt at using the legal system to force the government to become involved when there was a risk to a monument was the Bengal Regulation XIX of 1810.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The publication revealed the studies and polls that the society conducted to educate the public about India's ancient treasures.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Many antiques and other relics were quickly discovered during the ongoing fieldwork, and in 1814 they were placed in a museum.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Subsequently, comparable organisations were founded in Madras, Chennai, in 1818, and Bombay, Mumbai, in 1804.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] However, the most important of the society's achievements was the decipherment of the Brahmi script by James Prinsep in 1837.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] This successful decipherment inaugurated the asset.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Armed with the knowledge of Brahmi, Alexander Cunningham, a protégé of James Prinsep, carried out a detailed survey of the Buddhist monuments of his own type to be constructed in the Nepalese tarai which lasted for over half a century.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Inspired by early amateur archaeologists like the Italian military officer, Jean-Baptiste Ventura, Cunningham excavated *stupas* along the width, the length and breadth of India.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] While Cunningham funded many of his early excavations himself, in the long run, he realised the need for a permanent body to oversee archaeological excavations and the conservation of Indian monuments and used his stature and influence in India to lobby for an archaeological survey.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] While his attempt in 1848 did not meet with success, the Archaeological Survey of India was eventually formed in 1861 by a statute passed into law by Lord Canning with Cunningham as the first Archaeological Surveyor.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The survey was suspended briefly between 1865 and 1871 due to lack of funds but restored by Lord Lawrence the then Viceroy of India.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In 1871, the Survey was revived as a separate department and Cunningham was appointed as its first Director-General.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Cunningham retired in 1885 and was succeeded as Director General by James Burgess.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Burgess launched a yearly journal *The Indian Antiquary* (1872) and an annual epigraphical publication *Epigraphia Indica* (1882) as a supplement to the *Indian Antiquary*.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The post of Director General was permanently suspended in 1889 due to a funds crunch and was not restored until 1902.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In the interim period, conservation work in the different areas was carried out by the superintendents of the individual areas.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] From 1888 started severe lobbying aimed at reducing Government expenses, and at curtailing the budget of the Archaeological Survey of India, a period of about ten years known as the "Buck crisis", after the Liberal Edward Buck.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In effect, this severely threatened the employment of the employees of the ASI, such as Alois Anton Führer, who had just started a family and become a father.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In 1892, Edward Buck announced that the Archaeological Survey of India would be shut down and all ASI staff would be dismissed by 1895, in order to generate savings for the Government's budget.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] It was understood that only a fantastic archaeological discovery within the next three years for example might be able to turn public opinion and save the funding of the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Great "discoveries" were indeed made with the March 1895 discovery of the Nigali Sagar inscription, which succeeded in bringing the "Buck Crisis" to an end, and the ASI was finally allowed in June 1895 to continue operations, subject to yearly approval based on successful digs every year.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Another momentous discovery would be made in 1896, with the Lumbini pillar inscription, a major inscription on a pillar of Ashoka discovered by Alois Anton Führer.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The inscription, together with other evidence, confirmed Lumbini as the birthplace of the Buddha.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The organization was rocked when Führer was unmasked in 1898, and was found to file fraudulent reports about his investigations.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Führer had written in 1897 a monograph on his discoveries in Nigali Sagar and Lumbini, *Monograph on Buddha Sakyamuni's birth-place in the Nepalese tarai*, which was withdrawn from circulation by the Government.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Führer was dismissed and returned to Europe.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The post of Director General was restored by Viceroy and Governor-General Lord Curzon in 1902.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In a speech given to the Asiatic Society on 26 February 1901, he stated that he 'regarded the conservation of ancient monuments as one of the primary obligations of Government'.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Ancient Monuments Preservation Act was passed in 1904 during his tenure as viceroy.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Breaking with tradition, Curzon appointed 26-year-old Cambridge-trained archeologist John Marshall as the director-general of the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Marshall had experience with archeological excavations in Greece and oversaw reforms within the organization that consolidated funding and oversight over the local branches of the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] He served as the director-general for a quarter of a century and during his long tenure, he replenished and invigorated the survey whose activities were fast dwindling into insignificance.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Marshall established the post of Government epigraphist and encouraged epigraphical studies.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In 1913, he began the excavations at Taxila, which lasted for 21 years.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The most significant event of his tenure was, however, the discovery of the Indus Valley civilization at Harappa and Mohenjodaro in 1921.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The success and scale of the discoveries made ensured that the progress made in Marshall's tenure would remain unmatched.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Marshall was succeeded by Harold Hargreaves in 1928.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Hargreaves was succeeded by Daya Ram Sahni.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Dikshit both of whom had participated in the excavations at Harappa and Mohenjodaro.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In 1944, a British archaeologist and army officer, Mortimer Wheeler took over as Director General.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Wheeler served as Director General till 1948 and during this period he excavated the Iron Age site of Arikamedu and the Stone age sites of Brahmagiri, Chandravalli and Maski in South India.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Wheeler founded the journal *Ancient India* in 1946 and presided over the partitioning of ASI's assets during the Partition of India and helped establish an archaeological body for the newly formed Pakistan.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The National Museum was inaugurated in New Delhi on 15 August 1949 to house the artifacts displayed at the Indian Exhibition in the United Kingdom.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Madho Sarup Vats and Amalananda Ghosh succeeded Chakravarti.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Ghosh's tenure which lasted until 1968 is noted for the excavations of Indus Valley sites at Kalibangan, Lothal and Dholavira.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The *Ancient Monuments and Archaeological Sites and Remains Act* was passed in 1958 bringing the archaeological survey under the aegis of the Ministry of Culture.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Lal who conducted archaeological excavations at Ayodhya to investigate whether a Ram Temple preceded the Babri Masjid.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] During Lal's tenure, the *Antiquities and Art Treasures Act* (1972) was passed recommending central protection for monuments considered to be "of national importance".
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Deshpande who served from 1972 to 1978 and B.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] On Thapar's retirement in 1981, archaeologist Debala Mitra was appointed to succeed him - she was the first woman Director General of the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Nagaraja Rao, who had been transferred from the Karnataka State Department of Archaeology.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Joshi was the director general when the Babri Masjid was demolished in 1992 triggering Hindu-Muslim violence all over India.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] As a fallout of the demolition, Joshi was dismissed in 1993 and controversially replaced as director general by Indian Administrative Service (IAS) officer Achala Moulik, a move which inaugurated a tradition of appointing bureaucrats of the IAS instead of archaeologists to head the survey.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The tradition was finally brought to an end in 2010 when Gautam Sengupta an archaeologist, replaced K.M Srivastava an IAS officer as director general.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] He was again succeeded by Pravin Srivastava, another IAS officer.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Srivastava's successor incumbent, Rakesh Tiwari was also a professional archaeologist.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] His successor Usha Sharma was also an IAS officer and her successor V Vidyavathi who is the present DG of ASI is also an IAS officer.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Archaeological Survey of India is an attached office of the Ministry of Culture.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Under the provisions of the AMASR Act of 1958, the ASI administers more than 3650 ancient monuments, archaeological sites and remains of national importance.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] These can include everything from temples, mosques, churches, tombs, and cemeteries to palaces, forts, step-wells, and rock-cut caves.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Survey also maintains ancient mounds and other similar sites which represent the remains of ancient habitation.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The ASI is headed by a director general who is assisted by an additional director general, two joint directors general, and 17 directors.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The ASI is divided into a total of 34 circles each headed by a Superintending Archaeologist.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Each of the circles are further divided into sub-circles.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The ASI also administers three "mini-circles" at Delhi, Leh and Hampi.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Survey has had 32 Directors-General thus far.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Its founder, Alexander Cunningham served as Archaeological Surveyor between 1861 and 1885.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] India's first museum was established by the Asiatic Society in Calcutta (now Kolkata) in 1814.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Much of its collection was passed on to the Indian Museum, which was established in the city in 1866.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Archaeological Survey did not maintain its own museums until the tenure of its third director-general, John Marshall.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The ASI's museums are customarily located right next to the sites that their inventories are associated with "so that they may be studied amid their natural surroundings and not lose focus by being transported".
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] A dedicated Museums Branch was established in 1946 by Mortimer Wheeler, which now maintains a total of 50 museums spread across the country.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The ASI maintains a Central Archaeological Library in the Archaeological Survey of India headquarters building in Tilak Marg, Mandi House, New Delhi.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Established in 1902, its collection numbers more than 100,000 books and journals.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The library is also a repository of rare books, plates, and original drawings.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Survey additionally maintains a library in each of its circles to cater to local academics and researchers.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Mohammed Sanaullah Khan was appointed to the Archaeological Survey of India on 29 June 1917, marking the establishment of the Science Branch.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] His main responsibilities included preserving and chemically treating artefacts from museums and other artefacts.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] An Archaeological Chemist then oversaw the establishment of a laboratory at the Indian Museum in Calcutta, which was later moved to Dehradun in 1921–1922.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The scope and activities of the Science Branch greatly expanded along with the survey's expansion and shortly after Independence.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] These included doing in-depth study, treating monuments, analysing material remnants, determining the reasons behind deterioration, and taking corrective action for chemical conservation.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The day-to-day work of the survey was published in a series of periodical bulletins and reports.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] It consists of a series of seven volumes of inscriptions discovered and deciphered by archaeologists of the survey.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The bulletin has not been published since 2005.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] was first published by the then Director-General, J.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Since then, a total of 43 volumes have been published.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] An Arabic and Persian supplement to the Epigraphia Indica was also published from 1907 to 1977.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] A total of 27 volumes were published till 1990.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The first annual report was published by John Marshall in 1902–03.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The last volume was published in 1938–39.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] It was replaced by Indian Archaeology: A Review.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] as a bi-annual and converted to an annual in 1949.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The twenty-second and last volume was published in 1966.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] A Review: Indian Archaeology: A Review is the primary bulletin of the ASI and has been published since 1953–54.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] It replaced the Annual Report of the Archaeological Survey of India.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Apart from the ASI, archaeological work in India and conservation of monuments is also carried out in some states by state government archaeological departments.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Most of these bodies were set up by the various princely states before independence.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] When these states were annexed to India after independence, the individual archaeological departments of these states were not integrated with the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Instead, they were allowed to function as independent bodies.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In 2013, a Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) report found that at least 92 centrally protected monuments of historical importance across the country had gone missing without a trace.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The CAG could physically verify only 45% of the structures (1,655 out of 3,678).
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The CAG report said that the ASI did not have reliable information on the exact number of monuments under its protection.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The CAG recommended that periodic inspection of each protected monument should be done by a suitably ranked officer.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] The Culture ministry accepted the proposal.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In May 2018, the Supreme Court of India said that the ASI was not properly discharging its duty in maintaining the World Heritage Site of Taj Mahal and asked the Government of India to consider whether some other agency be given the responsibility to protect and preserve it.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In 2022, Ashish Avikunthak published a multi-year ethnographic study titled Bureaucratic Archaeology: State, Science, and Past in Postcolonial India with Cambridge University Press.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] In this work, he offers a rigorous and incisive critique of the functioning of the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Avikunthak reveals that systemic issues such as arbitrary transfers, delayed promotions, poor working conditions, and inadequate infrastructure reinforce the deeply entrenched bureaucratic structure of the ASI.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] He compellingly argues that this bureaucratic entrenchment, along with the religious politics embedded within institutional practices, profoundly shapes archaeological work in India and influences the nature of the evidence produced and presented as scientific fact.
[src:arikamedu/archaeological-survey-of-india] Five expert archaeologists who have also been working on Mohenjo Daro for many years—P.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Known as the city of gold and of the high fashion, Arezzo was home to artists and poets such as Giorgio Vasari, Guido of Arezzo and Guittone d'Arezzo and in its province to Renaissance artist Michelangelo.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In the artistic field, the city is famous for the frescoes by Piero della Francesca inside the Basilica of San Francesco, and the crucifix by Cimabue inside the Basilica of San Domenico.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The city is also known for the important Giostra del Saracino, a game of chivalry that dates back to the Middle Ages.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Described by Livy as one of the *Capita Etruriae* (Etruscan capitals), Arezzo (*Aritim* in Etruscan) is believed to have been one of the twelve most important Etruscan cities—the so-called Dodecapolis, part of the Etruscan League.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Etruscan remains establish that the acropolis of San Cornelio, a small hill next to that of San Donatus, was occupied and fortified in the Etruscan period.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Increasing trade connections with Greece also brought some elite goods to the Etruscan nobles of Arezzo: the krater painted by Euphronios c.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] 510 BC depicting a battle against Amazons (in the Museo Civico, Arezzo 1465) is unsurpassed.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Conquered by the Romans in 311 BC, *Arretium* became a military station on the via Cassia, the road by which Rome expanded into the basin of the Po.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arretium sided with Marius (157 – 86 BC) in the Roman Civil War, and the victorious Sulla (c.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] 138 – 78 BC) planted a colony of his veterans in the half-demolished city, as *Arretium Fidens* ("Faithful Arretium").
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The old Etruscan aristocracy was not extinguished: Gaius Cilnius Maecenas, whose name has become eponymous with "patron of the arts", came of the noble Aretine Etruscan stock.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Around 261 AD the town council of Arezzo dedicated an inscription to its patron L.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] See that article for discussion of the possible political/military significance of Volusianus's association with the city.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In the 3rd to 4th century Arezzo became an episcopal seat: it is one of the few cities whose succession of bishops are known by name without interruption to the present day, in part because the bishops operated as the feudal lords of the city in the Middle Ages.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The Roman city was demolished, partly in the course of the Gothic War and of the late-6th-century invasion of the Lombards, partly dismantled, as elsewhere throughout Europe.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The Aretines re-used the stones for fortifications.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The commune of Arezzo threw off the control of its bishop in 1098 and functioned as an independent city-state until 1384.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Generally Ghibelline in tendency, it opposed Guelph Florence.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In 1252 the city founded its university, the *Studium*.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The Tarlati sought support in an alliance with Forlì and its overlords, the Ordelaffi, but failed: Arezzo yielded to Florentine domination in 1384; its individual history became subsumed in that of Florence and of the Medicean Grand Duchy of Tuscany.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] During this period Piero della Francesca (c.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] 1415–1492) worked in the church of San Francesco di Arezzo producing the splendid frescoes, recently restored, which are Arezzo's most famous works.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Afterwards the city began an economical and cultural decay, which ensured the preservation of its medieval centre.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In the 18th century the neighbouring marshes of the Val di Chiana, south of Arezzo, were drained and the region became less malarial.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] At the end of the-century French troops led by Napoleon Bonaparte conquered Arezzo, but the city soon turned (1799–1800) into a resistance base against the invaders with the "Viva Maria" movement, winning the city the role of provincial capital.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In 1860 Arezzo became part of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] City buildings suffered heavy damage during World War II; the Germans made a stand in front of Arezzo early in July 1944 and fierce fighting ensued before the British 6th Armoured Division, assisted by New Zealand troops of the 2nd New Zealand Division, liberated the town 16 July 1944.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The Commonwealth War Graves Commission's Arezzo War Cemetery, where 1,266 men are buried, is located to the north-west of the city.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Pope Benedict XVI visited Arezzo and two other Italian municipalities on May 13, 2012.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo is set on a steep hill, rising from the floodplain of the River Arno.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In the upper part of the town are the cathedral, the town hall and the Medici Fortress (*Fortezza Medicea*), from which the main streets branch off towards the lower part as far as the gates.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The upper part of the town maintains its medieval appearance despite the addition of later structures.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo's city proper is near the high risk areas for earthquakes, but located in a transitional area where the risk for severe earthquakes is much lower than in nearby Umbria and Abruzzo, albeit it is slightly more vulnerable than Florence.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Notable earthquakes are still a very rare phenomenon in the province, with a 4.6 quake 25 kilometres (16 mi) to its north-east that claimed no lives on 26 November 2001 the exception.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*) with hot and dry summers combined with mild and rainy winters.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The annual average temperature is 13.54 °C (56.4 °F), the hottest month in August is 23.56 °C (74.4 °F), and the coldest month is 4.66 °C (40.4 °F) in January.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The annual precipitation is 864.03 millimetres (34.02 in), of which November is the wettest with 120.8 millimetres (4.76 in), while July is the driest with only 42.24 millimetres (1.66 in).
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo is home to an annual medieval festival called the Saracen Joust (*Giostra del Saracino*).
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] In this, "knights" on horseback representing different areas of the town charge at a wooden target attached to a carving of a Saracen king and score points according to accuracy.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Virtually all the town's people dress up in medieval costume and enthusiastically cheer on the competitors.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo hosts an annual popular music and culture festival each July, called Arezzo Wave.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Publicly funded, it attracts bands of high repute and attendees from all over Europe and North America and features some literary and film expositions.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo also hosts an annual international competition of choral singing Concorso Polifónico Guido d'Arezzo (*International Guido d'Arezzo Polyphonic Contest*).
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arezzo has a starring role in Roberto Benigni's film *Life Is Beautiful* (*La vita è bella*, 1997), which won three Academy Awards (Best Foreign Film, Best Actor, Best Original Score).
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] It is the place in which the main characters live before they are shipped off to a Nazi concentration camp.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Arretium was used in the PC game*Rome: Total War* as the Capital of the Roman Faction of Julii.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] The Piazza Grande is the most noteworthy medieval square in the city, opening behind the 13th century Romanesque apse of Santa Maria della Pieve.
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] Once the main marketplace of the city, it is currently the site of the *Giostra del Saracino* ("Joust of the Saracen").
[src:arikamedu/arezzo] It has a sloping pavement in red brick with limestone geometrical lines.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Sir Mortimer Wheeler 1945, and Jean-Marie Casal conducted archaeological excavations there in 1947–1950.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The site was identified as the port of Podouke, known as an "emporium" in the Periplus of the Erythraean Sea and Ptolemy.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Digs have found Amphorae, Arretine ware, Roman lamps, glassware, glass and stone beads, and gems at the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Based on these excavations, Wheeler concluded that the Arikamedu was a Greek (Yavana) trading post that traded with Rome, starting during the reign of Augustus Caesar, and lasted about two hundred years—from the late first century BCE to the first and second centuries CE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Subsequent investigation by Vimala Begley from 1989 to 1992 modified this assessment, and now place the period of settlement from the 2nd century BCE to the 8th century CE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Significant findings at Arikamedu include numerous Indo-Pacific beads, which facilitated fixing the period of its origin.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Red and black ceramics—known as megalithic stones or Pandukal in Tamil meaning "old stones" and used to mark graves—have existed at the site even prior to dates of the trading post, and also in later periods.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Arikamedu is a coastal fishing village, under the Ariankuppam Panchayat, on the southeastern coast of India, 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) from Pondicherry, on the Pondicherry-Cuddalore road; it was originally a French colonial town.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] It is located on the bank of the Ariyankuppam River (for most part of the year the river is considered a lagoon), also known as Virampattinam River, which forms the northern outlet of the Gingee River as it joins the Bay of Bengal.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] As the site is located at the bend of the river it provides protection to sea-going vessels that dock there.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The site has been subject to extensive archaeological excavations.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The archaeological site is spread over an area of 34.57 acres (13.99 ha) and has been under the control of the Archaeological Survey of India since 1982.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The name Arikamedu, an archaeological usage for the excavated site, originates from a Tamil word that means *Mound of Arakan*, based on the figurine of an avatar (incarnation) of the Jain Tirthankara Mahavira found at the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] It is also linked with Viraiyapattinam or Virampattinam, meaning *Port of Virai*, a village next to Arikamedu.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Virai, according to Sangam literature, was well known as a port and also for its salt pans during the Velir dynasty.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Arikamedu-Virampatnam together find mention as Poduke, a major port in the *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea* in the first century CE and as Poduke emporion in Ptolemy's Geographia of mid first century CE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Poduke is a Roman name and is also said to be a corrupted version of the Tamil name *Potikai*, meaning a "meeting place", also known for the local Poduvar clan.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The first mention about Arikamedu was in 1734, in a communication from the Consul of the Indo-French colony of Pondicherry.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] It informed the French East India Company that villagers were extracting old bricks from the Virampattinam.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The earliest mention of the Arikamedu archaeological site was by Le Gentil of France, who the King of France had assigned to observe notable astronomical occurrences in the world.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Gentil, after visiting Arikamedu, confirmed the earlier report of the Consul of the Indo-French colony.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] In 1765, when he visited the ruins at the site, he found the people of the village collecting large ancient bricks exposed at the river bank.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The villagers told him that they had retrieved the bricks from an old fort of the king the Vira-Raguen.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] In 1937, Jouveau Dubreuil, an Indologist, also from France, purchased gem stone antiquities from local children, and also gathered some exposed on the site's surface.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] In particular, he found an intaglio carved with the picture of a man.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] As a numismatist, he identified the intaglio as Augustus Caesar.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He concluded that these antiquities belonged to the Roman Empire.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Dubreuil informed the local Governor of Pondicherry about his find, and called Arikamedu "a true Roman city." He published a short note about his findings.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] In the early 1940s, Service des Travaux Publics carried out random excavations.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Father Fancheux and Raymand Surleau, who were not qualified archaeologists, carried out the excavations at Arikamedu and sent a few antiquities to Indian museums, and also to the École française d'Extrême-Orient in Hanoi.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Wheeler, the Director General of the Archaeological Survey of India, in the 1940s saw a few potsherds of Arikamedu site displayed in the Madras Museum, which he identified as *"terra sigillata"*, or Arretine ware, an expensive ceramic made until 50 CE in Arezzo, Italy.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Thereafter, when he visited the Pondicherry Museum and saw more of the findings from the Arikamedu site, he was impressed and thought that he had found the links between the Classical Mediterranean and Ancient India.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Soon thereafter in 1945, the penultimate year of World War II, he mounted excavations in a scientific manner.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He was looking for an archaeological site in India that could establish its cultural link, a datum of the Indian antiquities to the Greco-Roman period, and this quest led him to the Arikamedu site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] These excavations also involved Indian archaeologists, who were trained on the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He noted that, for the local fishermen of the village, the antiquities were strange—as they consisted of lamps, glass items, gemstones, cutlery and crockery, wine containers, etc.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He also observed that traders traveled from west coast and from Ceylon, Kolchoi (Colchi) and the Ganges area to trade goods such as gems, pearls and spices, and silk.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He carried out excavations carefully, so that none of the antiquities were damaged.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] This was followed by investigations after the war, from 1947 to 1950 by Jean-Marie Casal.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] His report of excavations was not as fully published as Wheeler's.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] His report was not well known in India, as it was not written in English.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] However, his important conclusion was that the site belonged to an early megalithic period, as he had located megalithic burials marked by stones, locally known in Tamil as *Pandukal* close to the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The excavations led to antiquities of Roman origin such as beads and gems, amphorae (wine making vats) with remnants of wine, a Roman stamp, big bricks recovered from an old wall, Arretine ware and so forth.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] From these antiquities Wheeler concluded that the site was related to a period of trading with Rome, and that it was first established by emperor Augustus.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He also noted that this Indo-Roman trade lasted for a period of about 200 years, till 200 CE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Wheeler also found the Chinese celadon, identified to belong to the Song-Yuan dynasty, and Chola coins from about the eleventh century, but these were rejected as despoiling items or remnants left by brick-robbers.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Items Chinese blue-and-white ware were also recovered from the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Wheeler noted that "rouletted Ware" found at the site (designated as "Arikamedu Type 1" in the scientific study under the "Arikamedu Type 10 Project: Mapping Early Historic Networks in South Asia and Beyond") was not of an Indian origin, but was from the Mediterranean region.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] A ceramic sherd, ("Arikamedu Type 10) has also been investigated for its style and spatial distribution.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] After a gap of several decades, in the early 1980s, Vimala Begley studied the ceramics find of the site and proposed a preliminary version of the chronology of the occupation of the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] At the same time she started researching on the beads, organized a proper sequential display of the artifacts of the site at the Pondicherry Museum, and brought out an information brochure.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Begley obtained approvals to carry out excavations at the site in collaboration with the University of Pennsylvania and the University of Madras; she and K.V.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Raman were the directors of operation from 1989 to 1992.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Steven Sidebothom of the University of Delaware, who had background knowledge of Roman Egypt, was in charge of the trenching at the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Further excavations were done during six working seasons from 1989 to 1992, which led to a contradictory view that the brick structures and the wells investigated by Wheeler were of poor quality as they were founded on poor sandy foundations.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The wood work was also noted to be of poor quality and the houses had no waterproofing.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The excavations also lead to a view that Arikamedu's Roman trading link was more of an inference.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The excavations have now established that the trading with Rome extended to a period beyond that assessed by Wheeler; that trading continued from the second century BCE to the seventh or eighth century CE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The extensive findings of glass and stone beads at the site provided Begley the link to Arikamedu's history.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] She identified the beads as *Indo-Pacific* beads crafted at Arikamedu.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Based on the antiquities and structural features from the excavations, Begley and Raman established a revised sequence of six major periods of occupation of the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Finds of new variety of Roman Amphorae ware also facilitated revision of the dates of occupancy.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] They have also inferred that the site has been in continuous occupation since at least 2nd or 3rd century BCE to much more recent times.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The excavated area of the mound was demarcated into two zones on the basis of occupation and elevation.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Northern sector of the mound is nearer to the sea coast while the southern sector is farther away from the coast.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The ceramic find of crockery and cooking vessels found in the northern sector were indicative of mass feeding of sailors and traders who camped there.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Wine stored in amphorae was the principal item imported from the western countries during the later part of the 2nd century BCE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] According to Wheeler the finds from the northern and southern part of the mound belong to the period from the later part of the 1st century BCE to the 1st and 2nd centuries CE.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Smaller objects include a wheel-turned blackware ceramic, a few terracotta figurines, shell beads, gems, gold, terracotta, iron nails, copper percussion beater, red fragment of a Roman lamp shade, an engraved emblem of emperor Augustus, an ivory handle, and a wooden toy boat.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Based on these antiquities Wheeler concluded that the Arikamedu was a Greek (Yavana) trading station.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] However, recent excavations by Begley have altered this assessment.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The buildings in the northern part of the mound indicative urbanization, with people of different ethnic groups—Indian and non-Indian—but it has not been possible to date them in view of the limited depth of excavations.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The excavation site also found few idols denoting ancient Tamils as the followers of Hinduism.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] H D Sankalia States that even though religious idols were rare in south India and Arimekadu was one of the rare sites where they excavated a statue of Brahma which was not found even in the northern part of India.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] Several other idols of Hindu gods were found in the site.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] H D Sankalia also states that the representation of Brahma was seated in a lotus similar to the brahma emerging from Vishnu's Navel.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] He further states that the Brahma Statue had a hole in the centre of the lotus so that the figure could be fixed on the peg of the stalk coming out from Vishnu's navel.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] An international conference that the Government of Pondicherry and the Italian Ministry of Foreign Affairs held in October 2004 decided to investigate the Arikamedu site jointly for conservation, as its ancient commercial link with the Romans has been established.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] During this conference, the Government of Pondicherry also decided to propose the site for status as a World Heritage Site of UNESCO.
[src:arikamedu/arikamedu] The Archaeological Survey of India also proposed the site for UNESCO Cultural Heritage Site status, under the title *Silk Road Sites in India*.
